      "content": "The consistent, small-scale disappearance of high-value electronics from a secure shelf is often indicative of \"shrinkage\" caused by internal processes rather than external theft, such as items being swapped out for lower-value goods before the count is taken or accidentally moved by warehouse staff during routine restocking. Another possibility is that the variance stems from unused stock being mislabeled as \"in transit\" or \"damaged\" and removed from the active inventory count without proper documentation. To pinpoint these hidden movements, consider reviewing recent shift logs for any unexplained breaks or scanning the system for items that have been temporarily moved to quarantine areas. Implementing a stricter \"last-out\" policy where every item leaving the shelf must be logged before closing the shift could help prevent these small but frequent losses.",
